    "For the single-epoch technique, (Bate et al. 2018) showed that low amplitudes of chromaticity, i.e.",
    "< 0.4 mag, defined as the difference of microlensing magnification between the reddest and bluest wavelengths, may yield slopes that are steeper than expected.",
    "On the other hand, the selection of observations displaying large amplitude of microlensing may systematically favour smaller sizes.",
    "Overall, simulations suggest that selection effects need to be carefully assessed when interpreting single-epoch measurements (Bate et al. 2018; Guerras et al. 2020).",
    "Monitoring data may be less prone to biases but the impact of sampling, number of bands, and length of monitoring on the results still needs to be quantified."
